On 5/12/07, Mark Baker &lt;distobj@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; On 5/11/07, Eric J. Bowman &lt;eric@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;  &gt; Has Microsoft&#39;s &quot;Windows Live Contacts API&quot; confused PUT and POST?
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; [1] http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb447763.aspx
&gt;  &gt; [2] http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb463980.aspx
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Specifically, isn&#39;t [1] a fine example of how not to use PUT?

[1] is wrong (I didn&#39;t bother looking at [2]). Let&#39;s make up a
document format to illustrate. You send a GET and receive this in
response:

&lt;foo&gt;
   &lt;bar&gt;1&lt;/bar&gt;
   &lt;baz&gt;2&lt;/baz&gt;
&lt;/foo&gt;

so it seems that [1] says

PUT

&lt;foo&gt;
   &lt;bar&gt;1&lt;/bar&gt;
&lt;/foo&gt;

will leave &lt;baz&gt; with content of 2, rather than not present at all.
That&#39;s pretty short-sighted, because it places application-specific
requirements on the server. If PUT meant PUT, then you could just drop
Apache in and the client would be none the wiser.

